58. The second opinion is (that) which limits sriendship to an equality of services and kind feelingS. This, indeed, is to call friendship to an account with too much minuteness and exactness, so that the amount of creditor and debtor may be equal. True friendship seems to me to be richer and more bountiful, and not to watch narrowly against paying more than it receives, nor must there be any sear lest anything should fall out or overssow to the ground, or lest any- thing more than what is sair should be heaped up on (the side of) friendship.
